metadata.name: Circus of Life #52
metadata.description:
Circus of Life is a playful take on my Clusters Algorithm, the basis for a 3D VR app developed in concert with the brilliant minds at Leap Motion. Clusters is like John Conway's "Game of Life", where just a few elegant rules in a toy universe generate endless complexity. 

Here, we spawn twelve "species" of particles. Each species is variously attracted to or repulsed by the other species, giving rise to wandering colonies, invasive blobs, and oscillating particle storms. 

For this new work, I collaborated with fellow algorithmic artist Canton Becker who sweated over the colors and genomes to expand its universe. Coded in just 46KB of vanilla javascript, each animation is minted with its own color palette, behavior, and mutations. Some special rarities have been seeded as well. Watch as microbial dramas play out and galaxies spawn. Will your circus be obscene or sublime?

metadata.name: Celestial Collisions  #558
metadata.description:
Celestial Collisions  - The following series is an exploration of organic textures that embodies the way of a gentle breeze and the simulation of color pencils that randomly generates simple shapes. Out of 380K different combinations of the following combinations,
an endless amount of orientations can be produced from the piece of work.  

For the interactivity element, turn on the (a)toms and check the pulsar settings.. on the interval the atoms will go from being almost invisible to standing front and center. Sometimes, you may need to look hard depending on the various atoms. 

* 's' - save an image of the current state 
* 'a' - activate atoms

The piece is to be experienced by default at 1000x1000, however, have fun with the image. It will adapt to various sizes and create different images by whatever size you view it in. 

@generatecoll 2021

metadata.description:

After resizing your browser window to a custom size, refresh the page or hit the F key. The sketch will then assume the new dimensions.

Due to the large amount of lines that have to be drawn this can take a couple of seconds.
Sorry, not sorry, if your browser explodes XD

metadata.name: Bound #228
metadata.description:
Knots bind and hold, mark time, and unite. But the power of a well-tied knot isn't only to fasten ‚Äì it also symbolizes how tightly one holds their pledges. Whether a commitment to a partner, community, or oneself ‚Äì the longevity of a deeply held bond is often marked with a symbol of passing time, like knots tied in a rope.

Let these ropes remind us of the binds we hold ‚Äì new ones, lengthy ones, unbreakable ones, and even those we‚Äôve had to untie. In plain view, these knots invite us to contemplate what our bonds mean to us, and to see them anew.

metadata.name: Bauhausstadt #65
metadata.description:
Bauhausstadt (Bauhaus City) is a series that draws direct inspiration from Ludwig Karl Hilberseimer's (September 14, 1885 ‚Äì May 6, 1967) work on city planning through a Bauhaus lens. Specifically, the series references his illustration from Bauhaus Magazine (Number 2, 1929) depicting a sustainable relationship between humans, industry, and nature. Hilberseimer proposed that this can be achieved through the construction of human habitation that ensures security for all people against disasters and crises.

This series explores Hilberseimer's use of "protective" architecture and repetition in his work, raising questions about the aesthetic and functional value of such an approach in urban planning. Through over 200 hand-drawn/coloured illustrations and a touch of randomness, the project visually poses this question and leaves it up to the viewer to decide its worth.

metadata.name: Barriers #76
metadata.description:
Barriers is an artwork+data visualization about the state of LGBT+ rights across the world.

Each edition is assigned 1 out of 197 countries. Four basic LGBT+ rights are represented as circles with barriers. The largest circle signifies whether homosexual activity is legal. The second-largest signifies same-sex marriage. The third one, same-sex adoption. The smallest one is the legality of gender change. One barrier means full rights. The more barriers, the more unequal rights are afforded to LGBT+ people.

The colors of the edition signify the country‚Äôs region and subregion.

The artwork adapts to different screen sizes and ratios, so I recommend exploring it on various devices or resizing your browser window.

¬∑ Interactions in-depth ¬∑

Desktop - S for save / D for dark mode / A for animate again

Mobile - Long press for save / Double tap for dark mode / Quadruple tap for animate again

Created using p5js and FettePalette. Data is from Equaldex.

metadata.name: Attractors Bestiary #51
metadata.description:
2D strange attractors have always been fascinating. Created from simple formulas, they are capable of generating a multitude of stunning shapes.

This generative program randomly creates and compiles a multitude of variations of a given attractor type. As a bestiary would show a selection of monsters, this one exposes these mathematical beasts. Each attractor can be viewed in full screen by clicking on it.

The available attractor types are:
- Clifford
- Clifford Squared
- Estienne 1
- Estienne 2
- Bed Head
- Fractal Dream
- Symmetric Icon

Artist: Estienne
Dec. 2021

metadata.name: Astraea's Loom #86
metadata.description:
A true collaboration of styles between Rose Jackson (@in_cloudlands) and Liam Egan (@neuromantic6).

Inspired by the weaving of cloth, this generative piece takes textures created lovingly by Rose and feeds it through a digital loom, weaving new cloth from the weft.

Preview images will differ slightly from the final output due to differing rendering methods in the preview system, and different resolutions may produce slightly different images.
